Meet Olivia, a Staffing Services Associate at Google. Raised on the Oneida Indian Reservation in Wisconsin, Olivia now works at our Mountain View headquarters and is a member of the Google American Indian Network. Wearing earrings and a necklace made of wampum, a traditional bead made out of quahog shells native to the East Coast, she says, ‚ÄúNative Americans have remained resilient through a long history of forced relocation by our ability to creatively adapt our values and ways to changing environments. Oneida‚Äôs traditional homelands are in New York, and like quahog shells, we represent our cultural legacies wherever we go. I‚Äôm inspired by incorporating my culture into my daily life, from simply wearing wampum jewelry to working with the Google American Indian Network, to make an impact in Native communities across the country. Our heritage is a strong fire that has been kept alive and protected through each generation and I am so honored to celebrate it today.‚Äù #NativeAmericanHeritageMonth

For #HispanicHeritageMonth, we‚Äôre celebrating the fascinating stories and important contributions of our Hispanic Googlers. Today we kick things off with Susanna, whose job is to help the 57 million U.S. Hispanics connect with Google, and ‚Äúbuild digital bridges‚Äù between Cuba and the rest of the world. ‚ÄúI am a product of the Cuban diaspora. My mother is American, my father was born in Cuba, and I was born in Miami. I grew up speaking two languages, blending between two cultures. Because I‚Äôm the product of a mix of cultures and nationalities, I understand the ambiguity of identity‚Äîhow you can belong and not belong at the same time. This has helped me to adapt to different environments and given me the ability to blend in, to understand, and to empathize.‚Äù

Meet Hector. Born in Venezuela and raised in Miami, Hector now works on our philanthropy team, Google.org, where he manages programs across Latin America, and supports our disaster relief giving and volunteer work globally. The most influential person in his life is his dad: ‚ÄúAs a first-generation immigrant, he taught me about risk-taking and tenacity. He‚Äôs always balanced family life with the needs of the community.
